'''Hong Myung-bo''' ({{langx|ko|홍명보}}, [[Hanja]]: 洪明甫; {{IPA|ko|hoŋmjʌŋbo}}; born 12 February 1969) is a South Korean football manager and former [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Defender (association football)#Sweeper (libero)|sweeper]]. He is currently the manager of the [[South Korea national football team|South Korea national team]].

Hong is widely considered one of the greatest Asian defenders of all time.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en-sg/news/3952/asia/2013/06/19/4058684/hong-myung-bo-strongest-candidate-for-south-korea-post |title=Hong Myung-Bo strongest candidate for South Korea post |publisher=Goal |date=19 June 2013 |access-date=23 September 2019}}</ref> He participated at four consecutive [[FIFA World Cup]]s between 1990 and 2002, becoming the first Asian player to do so. He also received the [[FIFA World Cup award#Golden Ball|Bronze Ball]] at the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]], becoming the first Asian to receive an individual award at the World Cup.<ref name="Bronze"/> He received some votes in elections for the [[FIFA World Player of the Year]], finishing 21st in [[1996 FIFA World Player of the Year|1996]] and 17th in [[2002 FIFA World Player of the Year|2002]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/1997/gennaio/21/Ronaldo_Weah_vincono_due_ga_0_970121984.shtml |title=Ronaldo e Weah, vincono in due |language=it |publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport |date=21 January 1997 |access-date=27 February 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.european-football-statistics.co.uk/special/old/bestplayer02.htm|title=FIFA World player 2002 Elected by 148 managers of national teams|publisher=European Football Statistics}}</ref> In 2004, he was selected for the [[FIFA 100]] by [[Pelé]].<ref name="FIFA100"/>

==International career==
=== 1990 World Cup ===
Hong was selected for the [[South Korea national football team|South Korea national team]] for the [[1990 FIFA World Cup]] just four months after his international debut.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://newslibrary.naver.com/viewer/index.nhn?articleId=1990053000289109003&editNo=4&printCount=1&publishDate=1990-05-30&officeId=00028&pageNo=9&printNo=631&publishType=00010 |script-title=ko:월드컵 축구팀 22명 최종확정 |website=[[Naver]] |publisher=[[The Hankyoreh]] |date=30 May 1990 |access-date=18 May 2020 |language=ko}}</ref> The youngest player at the team, he was one of the few South Koreans to be acclaimed, whlie they lost all three group stage matches.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://newslibrary.naver.com/viewer/index.nhn?articleId=1990061300329211003&editNo=3&printCount=1&publishDate=1990-06-13&officeId=00032&pageNo=11&printNo=13758&publishType=00020 |script-title=ko:崔순호·洪명보 두명만 뛰었다 |website=[[Naver]] |publisher=[[Kyunghyang Shinmun]] |date=13 June 1990 |access-date=18 May 2020 |language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://newslibrary.naver.com/viewer/index.nhn?articleId=1990062200209210003&editNo=2&printCount=1&publishDate=1990-06-22&officeId=00020&pageNo=10&printNo=21156&publishType=00020 |script-title=ko:마지막30초 虚찔렸지만 잘싸웠다 |first=Hong-ki |last=Han |website=[[Naver]] |publisher=[[The Dong-a Ilbo]] |date=22 June 1990 |access-date=18 May 2020 |language=ko}}</ref>

=== 1994 World Cup ===
Hong was selected for the [[South Korea national football B team|South Korea Universiade team]] for the [[Football at the 1991 Summer Universiade|1991 tournament]].<ref name="Universiade"/> He stabilised his team's defense, helping them advance to the final.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://newslibrary.naver.com/viewer/index.nhn?articleId=1991072300329111001&editNo=15&printCount=1&publishDate=1991-07-23&officeId=00032&pageNo=11&printNo=14119&publishType=00010 |script-title=ko:한국축구 U대회 "진군나팔" |website=[[Naver]] |publisher=[[Kyunghyang Shinmun]] |date=23 July 1991 |access-date=18 May 2020 |language=ko}}</ref> After a goalless draw with the Netherlands in the final, he scored his team's first penalty in a 5–4 penalty shoot-out win, contributing to winning the tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://newslibrary.naver.com/viewer/index.nhn?articleId=1991072500209219001&editNo=2&printCount=1&publishDate=1991-07-25&officeId=00020&pageNo=19&printNo=21542&publishType=00020 |script-title=ko:궂은 비 맞으며 활활 타오른 투혼 한국축구 유니버시아드制覇 |website=[[Naver]] |publisher=[[The Dong-a Ilbo]] |date=25 July 1991 |access-date=18 May 2020 |language=ko}}</ref>

Hong's talent started to receive attention internationally at the [[1994 FIFA World Cup]]. During the last five minutes of South Korea's opener against [[Spain men's national football team|Spain]], he converted opponents' 2–0 lead into a 2–2 draw by scoring a goal outside the penalty area and providing an assist for [[Seo Jung-won]]'s equaliser.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://newslibrary.naver.com/viewer/index.nhn?articleId=1994061900209101004&editNo=45&printCount=1&publishDate=1994-06-19&officeId=00020&pageNo=1&printNo=22546&publishType=00010 |script-title=ko:한국"「16强」보인다" |website=[[Naver]] |publisher=[[The Dong-a Ilbo]] |date=19 June 1994 |access-date=18 May 2020 |language=ko}}</ref> He once again scored a long-range goal in a 3–2 defeat to defending champions [[Germany national football team|Germany]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/usa1994/matches/match/3076/#match-lineups |title=GERMANY 3-2 KOREA REPUBLIC |publisher=FIFA |access-date=18 May 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://newslibrary.naver.com/viewer/index.nhn?articleId=1994062900289115005&editNo=5&printCount=1&publishDate=1994-06-29&officeId=00028&pageNo=15&printNo=1939&publishType=00010 |script-title=ko:94월드컵 한국 후회없이 싸웠다 |website=[[Naver]] |publisher=[[The Hankyoreh]] |date=29 June 1994 |access-date=18 May 2020 |language=ko}}</ref>

=== 1998 World Cup ===
Hong participated at the [[Football at the 1994 Asian Games|1994 Asian Games]] after the World Cup, but he injured his knee during a quarter-final match against [[Japan national football team|Japan]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://newslibrary.naver.com/viewer/index.nhn?articleId=1994101200209123003&editNo=45&printCount=1&publishDate=1994-10-12&officeId=00020&pageNo=23&printNo=22653&publishType=00010 |script-title=ko:「월드컵 스타」황선홍이 해냈다 |website=[[Naver]] |publisher=[[The Dong-a Ilbo]] |date=12 October 1994 |access-date=18 May 2020 |language=ko}}</ref> South Korea lost to [[Uzbekistan national football team|Uzbekistan]] in the semi-finals after he quit the competition.

While [[Park Jong-hwan (footballer)|Park Jong-hwan]] managed South Korea from 1995 to 1996, Hong was suspected of being in conflict with Park, who had a coercive disposition. The press reported that Hong formed a faction at the national team,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://newslibrary.naver.com/viewer/index.nhn?articleId=1996121700329116007&editNo=45&printCount=1&publishDate=1996-12-17&officeId=00032&pageNo=16&printNo=15968&publishType=00010 |script-title=ko:축구계「열하나회」있다 |website=[[Naver]] |publisher=[[Kyunghyang Shinmun]] |date=17 December 1996 |access-date=18 May 2020 |language=ko}}</ref> and doubted whether Hong did his best at the [[1996 AFC Asian Cup]], where South Korea was eliminated after a 6–2 quarter-final defeat to [[Iran national football team|Iran]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://m.pressian.com/m/pages/articles/69111?no=69111 |first=Hee-jun |last=Jeong |script-title=ko:기성용 전에는 홍명보가 있었다…"그러다 다친" 감독들 |publisher=[[Pressian]] |date=8 July 2013 |access-date=18 May 2020 |language=ko}}</ref>

Under [[Cha Bum-kun]], the next manager, South Korea had one draw and two defeats including a 5–0 defeat to the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] in the group stage of the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]]. Hong and his teammates conceded nine goals in three matches.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://newslibrary.naver.com/viewer/index.nhn?articleId=1998062200289118002&editNo=6&printCount=1&publishDate=1998-06-22&officeId=00028&pageNo=18&printNo=3225&publishType=00010 |script-title=ko:전술도 투지도 없었다 한국,최악의 수모 |website=[[Naver]] |publisher=[[The Hankyoreh]] |date=22 June 1998 |access-date=18 May 2020 |language=ko}}</ref>

=== 2002 World Cup ===
Hong was going to be selected as an overage player of the [[South Korea national under-23 football team|South Korea under-23 team]] for the [[Football at the 2000 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament|2000 Summer Olympics]], but he was injured just before the tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.joins.com/article/9025192 |script-title=ko:[런던2012]런던서 '올림픽 恨' 푼 홍명보 감독 |publisher=[[JoongAng Ilbo]] |date=11 August 2012 |access-date=18 May 2020 |language=ko}}</ref>

At the [[2000 AFC Asian Cup]], where South Korea finished third, Hong captained the national team, and was selected for the All-Star Team.

Hong led South Korea to a historic fourth-place finish at the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]]. He commanded South Korea's defensive line, which conceded only three goals until the semi-finals, and scored the final penalty to secure a 5–3 shoot-out win in a quarter-final match against Spain. Despite his error in the third place match against [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]], which was followed by the fastest goal in World Cup history,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/jun/29/worldcupfootball2002.sport8 |title=South Korea 2 - 3 Turkey |publisher=The Guardian |date=29 June 2002 |access-date=21 January 2026}}</ref> the Technical Study Group voted him as the third best player of the tournament, giving the Bronze Ball to him. He became the first-ever Asian player to be named one of the top three players at a World Cup.<ref name="Bronze"/>

That year, Hong ended his international career after a friendly match against World Cup champions [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]]. He was South Korea's all-time leader in appearances with 136 caps at the time,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/1285522-south-korea-2002-fifa-world-cup-retrospective#/articles/1285522-south-korea-2002-fifa-world-cup-retrospective |title=South Korea 2002 FIFA World Cup Retrospective |first=Allan |last=Jiang |publisher=Bleacher Report |date=5 August 2012 |access-date=23 March 2018}}</ref> and his record was broken by [[Son Heung-min]] in 2025.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/sports/20251010/son-heung-min-becomes-most-capped-male-player-in-s-korean-football |title=Son Heung-min becomes most-capped male player in S. Korean football |publisher=The Korea Times |date=10 October 2025 |access-date=10 October 2025}}</ref>

==Style of play==
Hong didn't have rapid pace, untiring stamina or outstanding ability in [[man-to-man defense]], but he possessed a wide field of vision as well as great leadership skills with which he marshalled his defensive partners.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://newslibrary.naver.com/viewer/index.nhn?articleId=1996120600289118001&editNo=6&printCount=1&publishDate=1996-12-06&officeId=00028&pageNo=18&printNo=2745&publishType=00010 |script-title=ko:공수핵 홍명보 약점보강 열쇠 |date=6 December 1996 |access-date=17 May 2020 |website=[[Naver]] |publisher=[[The Hankyoreh]] |language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hankyung.com/sports/article/2002060114478 |script-title=ko:[월드컵] 홍명보 수비라인복귀, `천군만마' |date=1 June 2002 |access-date=17 May 2020 |publisher=[[The Korea Economic Daily]] |language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sportalkorea.com/news/view.php?gisa_uniq=2015111907023253 |script-title=ko:[홍의택의 대담] 아시아의 리베로가 말한다, '한국 중앙 수비수' |date=24 May 2017 |access-date=17 May 2020 |publisher=Sportalkorea |language=ko}}</ref> An offensive [[Defender (association football)#Sweeper (libero)|sweeper]], he was noted for his accurate long-range passing skills which greatly contributed to South Korea's attack.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://newslibrary.naver.com/viewer/index.nhn?articleId=1997110200209111016&editNo=45&printCount=1&publishDate=1997-11-02&officeId=00020&pageNo=11&printNo=23697&publishType=00010 |script-title=ko:「홍명보 공백」못메우고 공-수서 몰락 |date=2 November 1997 |access-date=17 May 2020 |website=[[Naver]] |publisher=[[The Dong-a Ilbo]] |language=ko}}</ref> He was nicknamed the "Eternal Libero" by the South Korean media, and became a preeminent icon of South Korean football during his era.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.joins.com/article/15216909 |script-title=ko:'영원한 리베로' 홍명보, 24년 대표팀 영욕의 역사 |date=10 July 2014 |access-date=17 May 2020 |publisher=[[JoongAng Ilbo]] |language=ko}}</ref>

==Managerial career==
=== South Korea ===
On 26 September 2005, after his retirement as a player, Hong returned to the national team as an assistant coach. He took part in the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]], helping manager [[Dick Advocaat]]. He also worked with the next manager [[Pim Verbeek]] at the [[2007 AFC Asian Cup]]. After Verbeek's resignation, he was one of the candidates to become the next manager.

On 19 February 2009, the [[Korea Football Association]] (KFA) announced that they had appointed Hong as the manager of the [[South Korea national under-20 football team|South Korea under-20 team]]. At the [[2009 FIFA U-20 World Cup]], the team reached the quarter-finals under his guidance, but lost 3–2 to eventual champions [[Ghana national under-20 football team|Ghana]] in the quarter-finals.

In October 2009, he took over duties as a manager of the [[South Korea national under-23 football team|South Korea under-23 team]]. He won bronze at both the [[Football at the 2010 Asian Games – Men's tournament|2010 Asian Games]] and the [[Football at the 2012 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament|2012 Summer Olympics]]. He achieved South Korea's first-ever Olympic medal in football, also known as Asia's second.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/2.720/south-korea-blanks-japan-for-men-s-soccer-bronze-1.1211596 |title=South Korea blanks Japan for men's soccer bronze – CBC Sports |publisher=CBC Sports |access-date=23 March 2018}}</ref>

After working as assistant coach to [[Guus Hiddink]] at [[Russian Premier League]] club [[FC Anzhi Makhachkala|Anzhi Makhachkala]] for half a year, on 24 June 2013, Hong was appointed [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]]'s manager. His predecessor [[Choi Kang-hee (footballer)|Choi Kang-hee]] resigned voluntarily at the end of the [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification (AFC)|2014 FIFA World Cup qualification]], and he started to prepare the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]], which was going to be held after a year.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/sports/south-korea-name-hong-as-new-coach-idUSBRE95N046/ |title=South Korea name Hong as new coach |publisher=Reuters |date=24 June 2013 |access-date=11 October 2024}}</ref> After a winless World Cup campaign, on 10 July 2014, he resigned from his post.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |last=Yoo |first=Jee-ho |date=7 July 2024 |title=(3rd LD) Hong Myung-bo named new head coach for men's nat'l football team |url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20240707002153315?section=sports/sports |access-date=7 July 2024 |publisher=[[Yonhap News Agency]]}}</ref>

=== Hangzhou Greentown ===
On 17 December 2015, Hong was appointed manager of [[Chinese Super League]] club [[Hangzhou Greentown]]. In his first match on 6 March 2016, he guided the club to a 2–1 win over [[Changchun Yatai F.C.|Changchun Yatai]]. However, his team was relegated to the [[China League One]] after the [[2016 Chinese Super League|2016 season]]. The next year, he resigned from the club and criticised the club's owner for interfering in tactics and selection of players.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/sports/2024/10/600_230299.html |title=Korean coach blasts Chinese football club for 'EXCESSIVE' management meddling |publisher=The Korea Times |date=30 May 2017 |access-date=11 October 2024}}</ref>

=== Ulsan Hyundai ===
On 24 December 2020, Hong became the manager of [[K League 1]] club [[Ulsan HD FC|Ulsan Hyundai]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Ex-national football coach Hong Myung-bo takes over K League's Ulsan |url=https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/sports/2020/12/600_301406.html |website=[[The Korea Times]] |date=24 December 2020}}</ref> He led Ulsan to win two consecutive league titles in [[2022 K League 1|2022]] and [[2023 K League 1|2023]].<ref name=":0" />

=== Return to South Korea ===
On 8 July 2024, Hong was reappointed as South Korea's manager by KFA's committeemen in charge of finding a new manager.<ref name=":0" /> KFA president [[Chung Mong-gyu]], who preferred foreign managers to domestic managers, tried to interfere in the procedure, but Hong's appointment was not reversed by the support of executives and committeemen.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.khan.co.kr/article/202410021601001 |script-title=ko:문체부 “1순위 홍명보 먼저 만났다면 문제 없었을 것···계약 무효 판단 어려워” |language=ko |publisher=Kyunghyang |date=2 October 2024 |access-date=13 June 2025}}</ref> His team qualified for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]] with six wins and four draws without a defeat despite criticism about three consecutive draws in the middle of the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification – AFC third round|qualifiers]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.kyeonggi.com/article/20250326580357 |script-title=ko:홍명보호, 3연속 무승부…잇단 추가골 불발 ‘답답’ |language=ko |publisher=Kyeonggi Ilbo |date=26 March 2025 |access-date=13 June 2025}}</ref>

==Personal life==
In 1997, Hong married a woman five years his junior, and has two sons.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.donga.com/docs/magazine/woman_donga/200202/people14.html |script-title=ko:국가대표 복귀문제로 논란 이는 한국축구 간판스타 홍명보·조수미 부부 |language=ko |publisher=W Dong-A |access-date=22 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923223538/http://www.donga.com/docs/magazine/woman_donga/200202/people14.html |archive-date=23 September 2015 }}</ref>

